During the administration of American President '''[[Lyndon B. Johnson]]''' (1963–1969), the government made moves to reconsider cannabis law enforcement in the nation, including a more treatment-based approach to drug use. However, Johnson was saddled with controversies regarding the [[Vietnam War]] and internal national tensions, and was not able to make major changes to cannabis policy before declining to run for a second term in 1968.<ref name="Hudak2016"/>{{rp|47–48}} During the Johnson administration, cannabis usage was an issue of concern both in the youth counterculture as well as [[cannabis in the United States military|among American troops]] serving in the Vietnam War.<ref name="Hudak2016">{{cite book|author=John Hudak|title=Marijuana: A Short History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9qACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47|date=25 October 2016|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|isbn=978-0-8157-2907-5}}</ref>{{rp|46}}

==Presidency==
[[Federal Bureau of Narcotics]] chief [[Harry Anslinger]], a strong opponent of cannabis since the 1930s, left office in 1963, setting the scene for potential evolution of the national cannabis policy.<ref name="Hudak2016"/>{{rp|47}}

In 1966, the Johnson administration passed the [[Narcotics Addict Rehabilitation Act]], treating drug abuse as a medical issue similar to alcoholism.<ref name="Farmbry2014">{{cite book|author=Kyle Farmbry|title=The War on Poverty: A Retrospective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-LZKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=6 August 2014|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-9079-1|pages=93–}}</ref> Johnson's 1967 [[President's Commission on Law Enforcement and Administration of Justice]] concluded that the [[Marihuana Tax Act of 1937]] was ineffective, and over-broad in lumping cannabis use in with the more dangerous use of opiates.<ref name="SlabyTancredi1983">{{cite book|author1=Andrew E. Slaby|author2=Lawrence Tancredi|title=Collusion for Conformity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dnF9j1U1pPgC&pg=PA96|year=1983|publisher=J. Aronson|isbn=978-0-87668-709-3|pages=96–97}}</ref> Johnson himself considered the possibility of easing cannabis regulations by removing the [[mandatory minimum sentencing]] for cannabis possession.<ref name="Marion1994">{{cite book|author=Nancy E. Marion|title=A History of Federal Crime Control Initiatives, 1960-1993|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5XDdsrjdLmcC&pg=PA41|year=1994|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-94649-4|pages=41–}}</ref>

Throughout Johnson's administration, cannabis use rose sharply, with arrests increasing from 18,815 in 1965 to 61,843 in 1967.<ref name="Dufton2017">{{cite book|author=Emily Dufton|title=Grass Roots: The Rise and Fall and Rise of Marijuana in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo6YDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|date=5 December 2017|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=978-0-465-09617-6|pages=30–}}</ref> In response to the increasing usage of cannabis and other drugs, in 1968 Johnson placed the Federal Bureau of Narcotics ([[United States Treasury|Treasury]]) and the [[Bureau of Drug Abuse Control]] ([[Food and Drug Administration]]) under the control of the Department of Justice, consolidating them as the [[Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs]].<ref name="Delinquency1975">{{cite book|author=United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on the Judiciary. Subcommittee to Investigate Juvenile Delinquency|title=Marijuana Decriminalization: Hearing Before the Subcommittee to Investigate Juvenile Delinquency of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, Ninety-fourth Congress, First Session ... May 14, 1975|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-moTAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA487|year=1975|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=487–}}</ref>

