{{Infobox organization
| name                = South African Musicians' Alliance
| abbreviation        = SAMA
| region              = [[South Africa]]
}}

The '''South African Musicians' Alliance''' ('''SAMA''') is a union, [[artist collective]], and [[resistance movement]] formed by musicians in [[South Africa]] who opposed the [[censorship]] and [[Suppression of dissent|suppression]] of the [[apartheid]] regime.<ref name="Hall">{{cite book |title=The Oxford Handbook of Music Censorship |editor-last=Hall |editor-first=Patricia |chapter=Censorship from Apartheid to Post-Apartheid South Africa |page=597 |publisher=Oxford University Press |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eYc0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA597 |access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> The alliance was formed sometime before 1983.<ref>{{cite book |title=Soweto Blues: Jazz, Popular Music, and Politics in South Africa |editor-last=Ansell |editor-first=Gwen |page=190 |chapter=Jazz for the Struggle, and the Struggle for Jazz |year=2005 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_fwkCIKoTpgC&pg=PA190 |isbn=978-0-8264-1753-4 |access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> SAMA musicians flouted the government's imposed [[racial segregation]] and restrictions on music content.<ref name="Hall"/> Three of SAMA's priorities were [[freedom of speech]], [[freedom of movement]], and [[freedom of association]].<ref name="Hall"/>

One prominent spokesperson of the organisation was pianist Rashid Lanie.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sounding the Cape: Music, Identity and Politics in South Africa |last=Martin |first=Denis-Constant |chapter=Two Decades of Freedom |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2MU1vxkY16EC&pg=PA269 |page=269 |year=2013 |publisher=African Minds |isbn=978-1-920489-82-3 |oclc=855547885 |access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Rockin' the Boat: Mass Music and Mass Movements |last=Garofalo |first=Reebee |year=1992 |publisher=South End Press |page=196}}</ref>

